<EssayLayout {...meta}>
  <p class="tldr">
    <strong>TL;DR</strong>
    Just because you are qualified, it doesn&rsquo;t mean you will be hired or
    promoted. Even if you check all the boxes, you may still fall behind a certain
    candidate &mdash; because employers and management often don&rsquo;t need raw
    qualifications. They need alignment.
  </p>

  <p>
    If the corporate world solely cared about efficiency, the most qualified
    candidate would always win. Unfortunately, it doesn&rsquo;t work that way. When
    you become a manager, your instinct shifts toward protecting your inner circle,
    your existing structures, and your established workarounds.
  </p>
  <p>
    This reality forced me to realize a hard truth: under the current system,
    assuming I have what it takes, I cannot be promoted. Here is why.
  </p>

  <h2>1. The Threat of the High-Performer</h2>
  <p>
    Let&rsquo;s look at a common workplace scenario. You are an established manager
    in a company. Your team and the neighboring teams are doing just fine, and
    executive leadership assumes the operational ceiling has been reached.
  </p>
  <p>
    Then, a new manager is hired. He is the &ldquo;best candidate&rdquo; &mdash;
    deeply experienced and highly efficient. Suddenly, this new guy starts crushing
    KPIs and exceeding expectations across all aspects of the job. Executive
    leadership sees his potential and immediately puts him on the fast track for a
    promotion.
  </p>
  <p>
    But how does that make <em>you</em> feel? As a manager who has spent years
    trying to maintain a comfortable, &ldquo;chill&rdquo; job, that high-performer
    isn&rsquo;t a teammate &mdash; he is a threat who just raised the ceiling for
    everyone else.
  </p>

  <h2>2. The Invisible Behavioral Filter</h2>
  <p>
    Because of this friction, corporate survival kicks in. If you are the person
    trying to disrupt the status quo, the existing management structure will
    notice. In fact, you are being observed right from the start.
  </p>
  <p>
    The moment management hears that a disruptive high-performer is trying to apply
    for a promotion, they have often already rejected them in their minds. This
    rejection has everything to do with behavioral alignment. If you don&rsquo;t
    &ldquo;behave&rdquo; or act like a traditional manager &mdash; which often means
    protecting the peace rather than rocking the boat &mdash; you are filtered out
    before the interview even begins.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Departmental Monopoly</h2>
  <p>
    The final barrier to pure meritocracy is corporate feudalism, or monopoly.
    Imagine a company with five teams, and I am the boss of Team A. To secure my own
    political power, I will actively ensure that <em>my</em> team members are the
    ones promoted into neighboring managerial roles. If my co-managers used to work
    under me, I successfully maintain control over the entire department and secure
    my structure until I get promoted myself.
  </p>
  <p>
    Because promotion in this environment is strictly controlled, delegated, and
    vouched for, the game is rigged against outsiders.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    If you don&rsquo;t have that specific tribal connection, it doesn&rsquo;t matter
    how good you are &mdash; you will never get the position.
  </blockquote>
</EssayLayout>
